****************************************
The Rise and First Death of Nissan Motor
****************************************

Throughout most of Japan's automotive history, there were two companies in =
the lead: Toyota and Nissan. Everyone talks about Toyota. They are the unqu=
estioned giant and the champion of Japanese cars. But what about Nissan? Ho=
w did they come about? The history of Nissan Motor is a fascinating reflect=
ion of a world-famous industry. In today=E2=80=99s video, the rise and firs=
t death of Nissan Motor.

----------
Beginnings
----------

Nissan Motor's origins date to the 1910s. The family tree is exceptionally =
messy, so bear with me. Back then, a few enterprising Japanese dreamed of b=
uilding a car on Japanese soil. But most failed - producing a single protot=
ype before vanishing - because of the dominance of imports from Europe and =
America. Until 1911, Japan had just 43 domestically produced cars. The impo=
rts numbered over 600. People kept dreaming however. One of those people wa=
s Masujiro Hashimoto (=E6=A9=8B=E6=9C=AC=E5=A2=97=E6=B2=BB=E9=83=8E). A min=
ing and ironworks engineer, the Japanese government sponsored him to go to =
the United States to work at a steam engine plant. Upon returning in 1911, =
he started a small company called Kaishinsha Motor Works. The company did c=
ar repairs and assembled imported kits like those from Swift Motors in Cove=
ntry, England. But all the while, Hashimoto dreamed of making a Japanese au=
tomobile. He turned to three financial backers to fund that dream. The init=
ials of their surnames - Kenjiro Den, Rokuro Auyama, and Keitaro Takeuchi -=
 gave the car its name: DAT. Which in Japanese also means "escaping rabbit"=
 or "very fast". The DAT came out in 1914, and its basic 2-cylinder, 10-hor=
sepower design was inspired by Coventry's Swift car. The car wins a bronze =
prize in that year's Taisho Exposition and six more models were released un=
til 1917. However in 1920, Kaishinsha hits financial difficulties. Hashimot=
o designs a truck in an attempt to save the company with military orders. T=
he truck is ready by 1924, but those orders are meager. Deep in the red, Ka=
ishinsha liquidates. Its military business then merges with another early J=
apanese car company called Jitsuyo Motors - founded by an American who immi=
grated to Japan, William Gorham - to form DAT Jidosha Seizo in 1926. I will=
 just call them DAT Motors. Gorham had a side business as a consultant engi=
neer, and his best client was the business tycoon Yoshisuke Aikawa (=E9=AE=
=8E=E5=B7=9D=E7=BE=A9=E4=BB=8B). In 1930, Aikawa and his company Tobata Cas=
ting purchased a majority share of DAT. With this, Hashimoto left the compa=
ny he founded. He later reflected: =E2=80=9CMy life ended with sowing seeds=
. I sowed the seeds and nurtured them, but I could not reap the harvest.=E2=
=80=9D He passed away in 1944 at the age of 68.

---------------
Aikawa & Nissan
---------------

DAT's new owner Aikawa was raised in a prestigious but impoverished family,=
 and the experience seemed to instill in him a drive to succeed. Trained in=
 mechanical engineering at the University of Tokyo, he first worked at Shib=
aura Engineering, a workshop founded by the famed inventor Tanaka Hisashige=
 (=E7=94=B0=E4=B8=AD =E4=B9=85=E9=87=8D), the Thomas Edison of Japan. Many =
years later, Shibaura will merge with another company to form Toshiba. What=
 happened to them after that, I covered in another video. In 1905, Aikawa t=
raveled to rural America to apprentice in an iron factory. After returning =
to Japan, he founded the Tobata Casting Company in 1910, producing cast iro=
n fittings for foreign carmakers. Tobata did not exactly set the world on f=
ire but Aikawa was smart and driven. In 1928, a few years before acquiring =
DAT Motors, Aikawa was asked by his ailing brother-in-law to take over a fa=
iled mining company called Kuhara Mining. Kuhara owned Japan's second large=
st copper mine, the Hitachi Mine. But the company fell apart in the economi=
c recession after World War I and the great Kanto Earthquake of 1923. They =
were on the verge of bankruptcy. Aikawa turns the company around and restru=
ctures it as part of a new publicly-held holding company called Nippon Indu=
strial Company, or Nissan. Then in September 1931, the Japanese military st=
aged an explosion as a pretext to invade and occupy Manchuria. This ignomin=
ious event, as well a move off the gold standard that December, caused Japa=
nese stocks to plummet. Aikawa took advantage of the crash by scooping up d=
epressed shares on the cheap to form a new conglomerate: the Nissan Zaibats=
u. By 1937, they would control 77 companies, the third largest conglomerate=
 after Mitsubishi and Mitsui.

------------
Nissan Motor
------------

But let us drive back to little DAT Motors. In 1930, the Japanese governmen=
t issues a new regulation stating that drivers licenses were no longer requ=
ired for cars under 500 CC. So DAT Motors pivots to making mini-cars, with =
the aid of Gorman and engineers hired from the United States. Their minicar=
 hits the market in 1932, and is called the Datson, as in "son of DAT". The=
 name is later changed to Datsun with a =E2=80=9Cu=E2=80=9D since the =E2=
=80=9Cson=E2=80=9D in Datson as pronounced by a Japanese meant "loss" as in=
 "financial loss". Being competitively priced with contemporary imports lik=
e the British Austin Seven - 1,150 yen versus 1,600 yen - it does well. But=
 then the mushrooming Japanese war effort in Manchuria intervened. The mili=
tary needed trucks, and the country was importing them at an unsustainable =
cost of 40 million yen each year. So in 1932, a government committee design=
ed a standardized, domestic truck called the Isuzu and searched for busines=
s partners to help build it. The established Zaibatsu like Mitsui and Mitsu=
bishi were uninterested - the business class were largely critical of the m=
ilitary's aggressive actions. So the government gathered together DAT and t=
wo other small car companies - Ishikawa and the automobile division of Toky=
o Gas and Electric. I know. Tokyo Gas and Electric had a car division, who =
would have thought? When it became clear that the three were each too small=
, however, DAT merged with Ishikawa in 1932. But Aikawa apparently wanted t=
he merged company to make more than just cars and trucks for the military. =
He wanted to make passenger cars. And fortunately he still held the rights =
to make and sell DAT and Datsun cars. So in 1934, he took those rights and =
founded a new company called Motor Industries. This was then rolled into th=
e larger Nissan Zaibatsu and renamed to Nissan Motor. Nissan Motor produced=
 one of Japan's first automated production lines in Yokohama. In 1935, they=
 made 3,800 units and started exporting to Australia. That was good, but Ai=
kawa believed that to compete, domestic companies needed annual production =
of 10,000 to 15,000 cars. And they still fell short.

------------------
Nissan during WWII
------------------

Nissan Group harbored yet another valuable connection. Aikawa was distantly=
 related to Japan's conservative wartime leader Nobusuke Kishi. Powerful an=
d extremely controversial, Kishi is the grandfather of the late prime minis=
ter Shinzo Abe. They are not too fond of Kishi over there in China. Anyway.=
 In 1936, Kishi - urged on by Aikawa - passed the Automobile Manufacturing =
Law. The Law not only forced the domestic production of automobile parts, i=
t also granted Nissan and Toyota a licensed monopoly on car assembly operat=
ions in Japan. General Motors and Ford, their biggest competitors, were lim=
ited to just 12,360 units and 9,470 units. This essentially forced all the =
American carmakers to try and strike agreements with Japanese companies. Ni=
ssan struck a deal with the American carmaker Graham-Paige, buying the tech=
nology to build a car called the Nissan 70. Then in 1937, Japan formally en=
tered into war against the Republic of China. The military government centr=
alized control over the Japanese economy and compelled production of fighti=
ng trucks. Datsun and Nissan passenger car production ended in 1938. In Dec=
ember of that year, Aikawa had a plan to defuse looming tensions of war bet=
ween Japan and the United States. He moved Nissan Group's headquarters to H=
sinking - capital of the Manchukuo puppet state - changing their name to Ma=
nchuria Heavy Industries. His goal was to raise billions of yen to promote =
development in the puppet state, creating binding economic ties between the=
 United States, Japan and Manchukuo. Negotiations between Nissan and Ford o=
n a possible technology transfer partnership also continued. But Pearl Harb=
or ended both efforts. When war broke out, Ford's Japanese people burned th=
eir documents before being jailed. The government seized the American carma=
kers' factories, equipment and land for a nominal sum. After 1941, Japan's =
wartime efforts shifted from ground operations in Mainland China to naval e=
fforts in the Pacific Ocean. Frustrated, Aikawa left Manchuria for Japan in=
 1942. Nissan and its companies shifted to producing engines for planes and=
 torpedo boats.

--------
Post War
--------

Aikawa's closeness to the military government and his role in the occupatio=
n and exploitation of Manchuria led him to be labeled a war criminal by the=
 American occupation. Nissan Group was dismantled by the occupation and Aik=
awa removed as chairman of Nissan Motor in 1945. He was imprisoned for over=
 a year before being released. After that, he does not return to Nissan, bu=
t instead goes into politics. He never held a particular interest in Nissan=
 Motor. After the war, Japan's automobile industry laid in ruins - with sho=
rtages in everything from raw materials to capital to machines and so on. A=
 faction of the government led by the Bank of Japan advocated for letting i=
t go entirely. The governor of the Bank of Japan Hisato Ichimada said in 19=
49:

It is meaningless to develop the motor vehicle industry in Japan. Now is th=
e time of international division of labor. As we can get inexpensive motor =
vehicles of excellent quality from the United States, why don't we rely upo=
n them?

----
MITI
----

MITI disagreed. MITI of course, referring to the Ministry of International =
Trade and Industry. They believed that a vibrant car industry stimulated ot=
her parts of the ailing economy like machinery and steel. As well as brough=
t in foreign currency and prestige, stating:

Our country is one of twelve countries that produce passenger cars. These c=
ountries, except one or two, all are strong industrial countries. It is cle=
ar that in order to produce passenger cars a country's technical and indust=
rial standards must be at a high level

To nurture the domestic car industry back to health, MITI proposed restrict=
ions on foreign imports using commodity taxes, the careful allocation of fo=
reign currency, and of course high tariffs on foreign car imports. The Bank=
 of Japan opposed this. The Ministry of Transportation was not against it, =
but felt imports were necessary. But the outbreak of the Korean War and gro=
wing demand for passenger cars that followed convinced people that car impo=
rts were not sustainable. The high tariffs were crucial in protecting the J=
apanese car industry. Japanese-made cars were nowhere near competitive - MI=
TI themselves estimated the industry at 20-30 years behind. In 1952 Japan, =
an 8-cylinder Ford made in America cost just $167 more than a tiny Toyota T=
oyopet. But the Japanese car industry seemed to lack thankfulness for this.=
 As they developed and grew, the industry became rather resistant to taking=
 further "guidance" from MITI. Perhaps to the latter=E2=80=99s frustration.

--------
Kawamata
--------

In 1950, Nissan and Toyota shared the Japanese automobile industry, togethe=
r holding nearly 75% production share. But the entry of new competitors lik=
e Mazda, Mitsubishi, Honda, Fuji, and Daihatsu had eroded their grip on the=
 market. And then for Nissan in particular, the company was struck in 1953 =
by a major labor dispute. Workers demanded 20,000 yen a month, based on the=
ir calculations of a market basket. Being twice the average university grad=
uate salary, Nissan could not afford such a raise. So the strike went on. I=
n these days, Nissan had two major economic allies. The first was Hitachi. =
Nissan bought their electronic components from Hitachi, and Hitachi bought =
a lot of Nissan cars. I was unable to confirm if a Nissan-built engine powe=
rs their Hitachi Magic Wand. Their second ally was the Industrial Bank of J=
apan. For decades, much of Nissan's loans were made by this bank. The bank =
in turn garnered much of its profits from this client. So in the early 1950=
s, the bank lent to Nissan one of its executives Katsuji Kawamata (=E5=B7=
=9D=E5=8F=88=E5=85=8B=E4=BA=8C) to lead their accounting division. As the s=
trike dragged on, Kawamata was assigned to defuse it. During negotiations, =
he makes an alliance with a small, independent work group of college gradua=
tes. He encourages those guys to form a second union, the Nissan Motor Comp=
any Labor Union. And together they break the old union's hold over the work=
ers. Kawamata's actions formed a new, very cozy arrangement between Nissan'=
s management and its union. With major consequences down the line. But for =
now, it cemented Kawamata as the president of Nissan Motor. Inside the comp=
any, they called him the "Emperor". The labor strike allowed Toyota to surg=
e ahead of Nissan for the first time in the post-war era. So to catch up, N=
issan cooperated with the British Austin Motor Company on the Bluebird pass=
enger car. Foreign expertise helped make the Bluebird a success with taxis =
and rental cars and it remained their core offering for many years - drivin=
g Nissan to 66,000 cars made in 1960.

-------------
First Exports
-------------

Nissan first entered the American market in the late 1950s. They felt that =
Americans would be interested in buying Nissans as an economical second fam=
ily car. They showed off their small Datsun 1000 at the 1958 Imported Motor=
 Car Show in Los Angeles. Famously, Toyota exhibited their flagship Toyopet=
 Crown car there at the same show. The expensive car flopped in the market =
as it lacked the power or stability to handle America's open roads. They wi=
thdrew shortly thereafter. Nissan's cars sold a little better but can't hav=
e been called a success at the time. But Kawamata is determined and in 1960=
 they establish an American subsidiary to sign up dealers and help service =
Datsuns. A year later, they had signed up 122 dealers. The Toyopet's flop c=
aused Toyota to withdraw from the United States, leaving Nissan alone in th=
e United States for several years. By 1970, Nissan had sold over 170,000 Da=
tsun cars. Nissan also began their first forays into other regions at this =
time. In 1957 and 1960, they began exporting their own knockdown kits to Ta=
iwan and India, partnering with local companies for the assembly. They also=
 sent kits to Latin America. Mexico was a valued market and they built thei=
r first real factory, called CIVAC, in 1966 there. The lessons learned from=
 that helped with future expansions in North America.

----------------
A Miscalculation
----------------

Then came the 1960s, a time of growing national income for the Japanese. Ri=
cher Japanese wanted more cars and demand boomed. In 1960, MITI estimated o=
ver a million unit sales a year by the end of the decade. In 1965 alone, sa=
les hit 1.8 million. Moreover, tastes were shifting towards larger, more po=
werful cars with engine capacity of 700-800CC or higher. Such cars included=
 the Toyota Publica in 1961, the Mazda Carol 600 in 1962, and the Mitsubish=
i Colt 1000. Here, Kawamata misstepped. Nissan's most popular car at the ti=
me was the small Bluebird. Kawamata was afraid of that making these larger,=
 more powerful "popular cars" would cannibalize Bluebird sales, so he preve=
nted their development. This misstep allowed Toyota to surge ahead in passe=
nger car market share with the Publica. Nissan scrambled to get back in the=
 game with a model called the Sunny, but low volume put them on their back =
foot.

------
Merger
------

In steps MITI. Fearing oversupply, they had been throughout the 1960s tryin=
g to convince Japan's eight or so carmakers to consolidate. They tried to m=
erge the smaller ones into a third player alongside Toyota and Nissan. They=
 tried to forbid Honda from entering the industry, though Soichiro Honda is=
 so based he doesn't care about that. But anyway, it was in that spirit of =
consolidation that MITI suggests that Nissan merge with the struggling car =
company, Prince Motor. Prince dates back to two pre-War aircraft companies.=
 When aircraft production was banned after the War, the two started making =
cars. They first made an electric car, which was well received but the Kore=
an War boom caused them to switch to gas-powered trucks. In the late 1950s,=
 Prince drew on their aircraft heritage to release a series of high-perform=
ance cars like the Skyline and Prince Gloria. But intense competition and a=
 weakness in sales and marketing left them with poor revenue, a large inven=
tory, and rising debt. So Prince's president reached out to various merger =
partners through their bank. Toyota turned them down, smelling a raging dum=
pster fire beneath the covers. But Nissan saw Prince as a way to get back i=
nto a category in which they were behind, and with MITI's mediation negotia=
ted a merger in 1965. The merger had some upsides and downsides. It brought=
 the company into a brand new world of high-performance sports and racing c=
ars like the Z-series and the Nissan GT-R. But at the same time, the merger=
 also planted the seed for future troubles. Prince indeed had many problems=
. And adding sporty cars to the lineup might have delighted the world's car=
-heads, but it stuck out like a sore thumb in a company that produced Blueb=
irds. And merging the labor unions set the stage for even more serious prob=
lems. Nissan's labor union, working hand in hand with management, demanded =
that Prince's labor union close. This preserved labor peace, but essentiall=
y made the Nissan union a member of management - with bad consequences in t=
he future.

----------------
Global Expansion
----------------

The growing focus on emissions - starting with the Muskie Law of 1970 - fol=
lowed by the oil crises of the 1970s sparked massive American demand for sm=
aller, more economic Japanese cars. The American carmakers were forced to d=
evelop new, cleaner running engines, which cost money. Then inflation in th=
at decade triggered rapid wage increase clauses for union workers, worsenin=
g their cost basis against the Japanese. After a second oil crisis hit in 1=
979, the Japanese automobile companies surged ahead of the Americans with c=
ars like the Datsun 210, which could go 41 miles on a single gallon of gas.=
 Nissan leaned into the environmental message with slogans like "Drive a Da=
tsun, Plant a Tree". And the notion worked. A third of all the cars sold we=
re Japanese small cars. Nearly 2 million cars were being imported each year=
. Japan became one of the world's top car-making nations, but the export bo=
om caused major geopolitical tensions. A political agreement in 1981 negoti=
ated a cap on Japanese car imports, forcing the Japanese to move production=
 abroad. While investigations for a US plant were being done in the mid-197=
0s - based on learnings from their Mexico plant in the 1960s - it was not u=
ntil April 1980 that they announced their first American plant in the city =
of Smyrna, Tennessee. It was completed in 1982. Nissan's new president Taka=
shi Ishihara then pushed the company into a massive globalization drive tha=
t saw them opening factories across various other countries. In 1984, they =
announced that they would open a plant in Sunderland in northeast England. =
That plant remains open to this day, producing cars like the Leaf. The comp=
any also struck cooperative deals with local companies in Spain, West Germa=
ny and Italy. Nissan's seeming success in transplanting their practices cam=
e as a surprise. How can a Nissan factory in the United States and Europe s=
till be so productive? Business scholars talked of the company's unique hyb=
ridization strategy and ability to create togetherness across cultures.

---------
The 1990s
---------

Then came the 1990s, a time of reversal for Nissan and the other Japanese c=
armakers. Every year from 1992 to 1998, Nissan turned losses except for 199=
6. The popping of the real estate bubble deeply damaged the company's home =
market. For the eight Japanese car makers, profits in Japan fell from a pea=
k of nearly $12 billion in 1989 to $4.2 billion in 1992, a two-thirds loss.=
 One major issue was that Nissan, like Toyota, simply had too many of the s=
ame cars. Japanese consumers wanted cheaper cars, or migrated to minivans, =
SUVs and Recreational Vehicles, RVs. But Toyota ably responded while Nissan=
 failed to keep up with the trend, either producing too many of the wrong c=
ars, or too few of the right ones - causing the latter to be too expensive.=
 In 1990, Nissan sold 1.38 million cars at home. By 1998, they sold just 86=
1,411. And the appreciation of the Japanese yen laid waste to the company's=
 bottom lines. In 1993, Nissan saved 150 billion yen by consolidating parts=
, but then gave back nearly half of that in currency losses alone. Overseas=
, Nissan's aggressive globalization strategy became a drag. Operations in S=
pain and Mexico started losing money. And in the United States, the Big Thr=
ee bounced back with new products and a refocused effort on productivity. H=
ow the turntables turn! Nissan did no favors for themselves by undertaking =
an expensive, controversial and confusing brand change from Datsun to Nissa=
n in the 1980s, costing hundreds of millions of dollars. Kawamata later reg=
retted naming Ishihara as president of Nissan, seeing the globalization mov=
e of the 1980s as being driven by politics rather than economics. Ishihara =
wanted Nissan to be a model for other Japanese carmakers and pushed ahead a=
s the guinea pig. And finally, the company's years of acquiring and assimil=
ating technologies and businesses to accomplish its goals had left it with =
a high cost structure and unproductive workers. Dealing with such a complex=
 structure was complicated by its relations with its union. Over the decade=
s the Nissan labor union, once so cooperative, had created almost a system =
of dual management that left it with a bloated, unproductive workforce part=
icularly at home.

---------
First End
---------

Worst of all, the company's heavy debt balance, a load estimated at $22 bil=
lion, hung over them. The company attempted to save itself with a series of=
 restructuring plans. The first plan in 1993 involved one of its first ever=
 Japanese plant closures, the Zama plant, and the elimination of 5000 jobs.=
 It was their second oldest plant. Now far too old and too small to be usef=
ul - the suburbs of Tokyo had basically expanded around them. But it still =
took 2 years to actually close. In 1997, Nissan's North American operations=
 started seriously deteriorating from an aging lineup. Things came to a hea=
d the following year May 1998 when a stock market crash damaged the company=
's portfolio of shareholdings, forcing management to seek the help of a for=
eign partner. That year saw many consolidations, the biggest was the merger=
 between Daimler-Benz AG and Chrysler Corporation to form DaimlerChrysler. =
Nissan negotiated with DaimlerChrysler and then Ford in the hopes of a part=
nership, but those fell through. Finally in May 1999, the company signed a =
deal with the French carmaker Renault.

----------
Conclusion
----------

Throughout the century, Toyota and Nissan took wildly different approaches =
to their business. Toyota is an engineering-led organization, focused on pr=
oducing popular cars with their own internally developed technologies. Niss=
an on the other hand was different. They were led by bankers and administra=
tors. They bought and assimilated foreign technologies as needed. And exhib=
ited a haphazard management style that frequently caused them to fall behin=
d on the latest trends. And out of all the big Japanese carmakers, Nissan w=
as the one closest to the government's industrial policymakers. So much so =
that they nicknamed the Nissan HQ building in the Ginza area, the "MITI of =
Ginza". Meaning that in many ways, Nissan was more about policy and doing w=
hat the government wanted rather than actually doing what was best for the =
company. That swank 16-story building in Ginza was eventually sold off for =
cash during the crisis period. A symbol of the company's dire straits situa=
tion. And an opportunity for a revitalizing force from abroad.

